{{Infobox academic|name=Emma Kowal|residence=Australia|nationality=Australian|occupation=anthropologist, physician, public health researcher, professor|awards=Paul Bourke Award for Early Career Research|education=University of Melbourne (BA, MBBS, PhD)|discipline=medical anthropology, public health|workplaces=Deakin University}}
'''Emma Kowal''' is an Australian cultural and medical anthropologist, physician and scholar of science and technology studies. She is most well-known for her books ''Trapped in the Gap: Doing Good in Indigenous Australia''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/896862152|title=Trapped in the gap : doing good in indigenous Australia|last=Emma.|first=Kowal,|isbn=9781782385998|location=New York|oclc=896862152}}</ref>, and the co-edited volumes of ''Force, Movement, Intensity: The Newtonian Imagination in the Humanities and Social Sciences''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/721261932|title=Force, movement, intensity|last=Ghassan.|first=Hage,|date=2011|publisher=Melbourne University Publishing|others=Kowal, Emma.|isbn=9780522860818|location=Carlton, Vic.|oclc=721261932}}</ref> (with [[Ghassan Hage]]), ''Cryopolitics: Frozen Life in a Melting World''<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/979560265|title=Cryopolitics : frozen life in a melting world|others=Radin, Joanna,, Kowal, Emma,|isbn=9780262338691|location=Cambridge, MA|oclc=979560265}}</ref> (with [[Joanna Radin]]).
==Early life and education== She received her Bachelor of Medicine and Bachelor of Surgery and a Bachelor of Arts in history and philosophy of science from [[University of Melbourne]] in 2000 and worked for a few years as a physician and a public health professional in the Northern Territories of Australia. She returned to the University of Melbourne to receive her PhD in public health anthropology in 2007. She is currently an Associate Professor in Anthropology at [[Deakin University]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.deakin.edu.au/about-deakin/people/emma-kowal|title=Emma Kowal|last=University|first=Deakin|website=www.deakin.edu.au|language=en|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>.
==Career== In 2014, she received the Paul Bourke Award for Early Career Research from the [[Academy of the Social Sciences in Australia]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.assa.edu.au/awards/|title=Awards » ASSA|website=www.assa.edu.au|language=en-US|access-date=2018-10-19}}</ref>. She was the deputy director for the [[National Centre for Indigenous Genomics]] at [[Australian National University]] between 2013 and 2017<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://ncig.anu.edu.au/people/emma-kowal|title=Professor Emma Kowal|last=NCIG|first=Director,|date=2013-12-10|work=NCIG|access-date=2018-10-19|last2=jcsmr.ncig@anu.edu.au|language=en}}</ref>.
==Publications== Emma Kowal has contributed to a large number of scholarly articles.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://scholar.google.com/citations?user=BtbJ1LAAAAAJ&hl=en|title=Emma Kowal|publisher=Google Scholar|accessdate=19 October 2018 |language=}}</ref>
