{{globalize|date=March 2017}} '''Industrial waste''' is the waste produced by industrial activity which includes any material that is rendered useless during a manufacturing process such as that of [[factories]], industries, mills, and mining operations. It has existed since the start of the [[Industrial Revolution]].<ref>{{cite book |last=Maczulak |first=Anne Elizabeth |year=2010 |title=Pollution: Treating Environmental Toxins |url= |location=New York |publisher=Infobase Publishing |page=120 |isbn=9781438126333}}</ref> Some examples of industrial wastes are [[chemical solvent]]s, pigments, sludge, metals, ash, paints, sandpaper, paper products, industrial [[by-products]], and [[radioactive wastes]].
[[Toxic waste]], [[chemical waste]], industrial solid waste and [[municipal solid waste]] are designations of industrial wastes. [[Sewage treatment]] plants can treat some industrial wastes, i.e. those consisting of [[conventional pollutant]]s such as [[biochemical oxygen demand]] (BOD). Industrial wastes containing [[toxic]] pollutants require specialized treatment systems. (''See'' [[Industrial wastewater treatment]]).<ref>U.S. Environmental Protection Agency, Washington, DC (2011). [http://www.epa.gov/npdes/pubs/pretreatment_program_intro_2011.pdf "Introduction to the National Pretreatment Program"] Document no. EPA-833-B-11-001. pp. 1-1, 1-2.</ref>
== Environmental Impact == Production sites are commonly located near bodies of water due to industrial dependence on large amounts of water as an input. Many areas that are becoming industrialized do not yet have the resources or technology to dispose of waste with lesser effects on the environment. Both untreated and partially treated wastewater are commonly fed back into a near lying body of water. Metals, chemicals and sewage released into bodies of water directly affect marine ecosystems and the health of those who depend on the waters as food or drinking water sources. Toxins from the wastewater can kill off marine life or cause varying degrees of illness to those who consume these marine animals, depending on the contaminant. Metals and chemicals released into bodies of water affect the [[Marine ecosystem|marine ecosystems]]. <ref>{{Cite book|title=Wastes in Marine Environments|last=U.S. Congress|first=Office of Technology’ Assessment|publisher=Washington, DC: U.S. Government Printing Office|year=1987|isbn=|location=Washington, DC|pages=22}}</ref> Wastewater containing nitrates and phosphates often causes [[Eutrophication]] which can kill off existing life in the water. A Thailand study focusing on water pollution origins found that the highest concentrations of water contamination in the U-tapao river had a direct correlation to industrial wastewater. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Gyawali at al.|first=|date=2012|title=Effects of Industrial Waste Disposal on the Surface Water Quality of U-tapao River, Thailand|url=http://www.ipcbee.com/vol32/019-ICESE2012-D10030.pdf|journal=2012 International Conference on Environment Science and Engieering|volume=32|pages=5|via=}}</ref>
==Management==
===In Thailand=== {{Main|Industrial waste management in Thailand}}
In [[Thailand]] the roles in [[Municipal solid waste|Municipal solid waste (MSW)]] management and industrial waste management are organized by the Royal Thai Government, which is then divided into central government, regional government, and local government. Each government is responsible for different tasks. The central government is responsible for stimulating regulation, policies, and standards. The regional governments are responsible for coordinating the central and local governments. The local governments are responsible for waste management in their governed area.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jiaranaikhajorn|first1=Taweechai|title=Waste and Hazardous Substances Management Bureau|url=http://infofile.pcd.go.th/mgt/Overview_waste.pdf?CFID=818746&CFTOKEN=13734972|publisher=Pollution Control Department (PCD), THAILAND|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> However, the local governments do not dispose of the waste by themselves but instead hire private companies that have been granted the right from the Pollution Control Department (PCD) in Thailand.<ref>{{cite web|title=Pollution Control Department (PCD) Statement, THAILAND|url=http://www.pcd.go.th/about/en_ab_mission.html|publisher=Ministry of Natural Resources and Environment|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111161400/http://www.pcd.go.th/about/en_ab_mission.html|archivedate=2014-11-11|df=}}</ref> The main companies are Bangpoo Industrial Waste Management Center,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Visvanathan|first1=C.|title=Hazardous and Industrial Solid Waste Management in Thailand - an Overview|url=http://www.jgsee.kmutt.ac.th/jgsee1/NewsEvents/Seminar/ISSOWAMA/Visvanathan_Presentation.pdf|website=www.faculty.ait.ac.th/visu/|publisher=Asian Institute of Technology Thailand|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> General Environmental Conservation Public Company Limited (GENCO),<ref>{{cite web|title=Genco Background|url=http://www.genco.co.th/EN-About.htm|publisher=General Environment Conservation Public Company Limited (GENCO)|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> SGS Thailand,<ref>{{cite web|title=About SGS|url=http://www.sgs.co.th/en/Our-Company/About-SGS/Sponsorship.aspx|publisher=SGS (Thailand) Limited|accessdate=22 November 2014|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141111172910/http://www.sgs.co.th/en/Our-Company/About-SGS/Sponsorship.aspx|archivedate=11 November 2014|df=}}</ref> Waste Management Siam LTD (WMS),<ref>{{cite web|title=About Waste Management Siam LTD. (WMS)|url=http://www.wms-thailand.com|publisher=Waste Management Siam LTD.|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> and Better World Green Public Company Limited (BWG).<ref>{{cite web|title=About BGW|website=http://www.betterworldgreen.com/|publisher=Better World Green Public Company Limited (BWG)|accessdate=22 November 2014}}</ref> These companies are responsible for the waste they have received from their customers before releasing it to the environment, burying it.
===In the United States=== {{main|Solid waste policy in the United States}} The 1976 [[Resource Conservation and Recovery Act]] (RCRA) provides for federal regulation of waste while allowing for individual state control through [[EPA]] approved waste disposal programs.
State compliance is monitored by EPA inspections. In the case that waste management guideline standards are not met, action against the site will be taken. Compliance errors may be corrected by enforced cleanup directly by the site responsible for the waste or by a third party hired by that site.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.epa.gov/rcra/resource-conservation-and-recovery-act-rcra-overview#howdoesrcrawork|title=Resource Conservation and Recovery Act (RCRA) Overview {{!}} US EPA|last=EPA,OSWER,ORCR|first=US|website=US EPA|language=en|access-date=2018-09-07}}</ref> Prior to this act, open dumping or releasing wastewater into nearby bodies of water were common waste disposal methods. <ref>{{Cite journal|last=Brown et. al|first=|date=June 1977|title=Reassessing the History of U.S. Hazardous Waste Disposal Policy - Problem Definition, Expert Knowledge and Agenda-Setting|url=https://scholars.unh.edu/cgi/viewcontent.cgi?article=1332&context=risk|journal=Risk: Health, Safety and Environment (1990-2002)|volume=8|pages=26|via=}}</ref> The negative externalities on human health and environmental health led to the need for such a regulations. The RCRA framework provides specified subsections defining nonhazardous and hazardous waste materials and how each should be properly managed and disposed of. Guidelines for the disposal of nonhazardous solid waste includes the banning of open dumping. Hazardous waste is monitored in a [[cradle to grave]] fashion.The EPA now manages 2.96 million tons of solid, hazardous and industrial waste. Since establishment, the RCRA has undergone reforms as inefficiencies arise and as waste management evolves. <ref name=":0" />
